[2026-06-11T02:45:23.508Z] [THINK]
So `g_node` is used in the keyboard thread (which runs as
[/THINK]
[2026-06-11T02:45:23.950Z] [THINK]
 a pthread, not an rclcpp thread) to call `rclcpp::spin_until_future_complete`. This function needs a node
[/THINK]
[2026-06-11T02:45:24.388Z] [THINK]
 to spin its executor — it's the ROS2 equivalent of spinning until an
[/THINK]
[2026-06-11T02:45:24.834Z] [THINK]
 async service call completes.

The thread can't use the local `node` from `main()` because the thread function
[/THINK]
[2026-06-11T02:45:25.279Z] [THINK]
 signature is `void* func(void*)` — it receives a `
[/THINK]
[2026-06-11T02:45:25.690Z] [THINK]
void*` arg, not a `shared_ptr<Node>`. So the global `g_node` is a workaround to share the
[/THINK]
[2026-06-11T02:45:26.115Z] [THINK]
 node pointer across threads.

A cleaner alternative would be to pass the node pointer via the thread's `
[/THINK]
[2026-06-11T02:45:26.525Z] [THINK]
void*` argument (the `cmd_handler` thread creation), which would eliminate
[/THINK]
[2026-06-11T02:45:26.960Z] [THINK]
 the global entirely. But that's a separate refactor.
[/THINK]
