[2026-06-11T03:31:13.342Z] [THINK]
The user
[/THINK]
[2026-06-11T03:31:13.751Z] [THINK]
 is asking why PIDControl.cpp uses the Pimpl (pointer-to-implementation) idiom with
[/THINK]
[2026-06-11T03:31:14.190Z] [THINK]
 two classes (PIDImpl and PID), and whether they can be merged into one.

Re
[/THINK]
[2026-06-11T03:31:14.602Z] [THINK]
asons for Pimpl here:
1. The header `PIDControl.h` exposes only the
[/THINK]
[2026-06-11T03:31:15.046Z] [THINK]
 `PID` class with a forward-declared `PIDImpl* pimpl` — the implementation details
[/THINK]
[2026-06-11T03:31:15.451Z] [THINK]
 (filter state, coefficients, etc.) are hidden from users of the header
[/THINK]
[2026-06-11T03:31:15.874Z] [THINK]

2. This means code that includes `PIDControl.h` doesn't need to recompile when PIDImpl intern
[/THINK]
[2026-06-11T03:31:16.313Z] [THINK]
als change

However, looking at this codebase:
- The header already doesn
[/THINK]
[2026-06-11T03:31:16.750Z] [THINK]
't expose much
- The PIDImpl class is defined entirely in the .cpp file
-
[/THINK]
[2026-06-11T03:31:17.183Z] [THINK]
 There's no real ABI stability concern
- The `#include <list
[/THINK]
[2026-06-11T03:31:17.614Z] [THINK]
>` in the header is already leaking that detail
- The codebase is a single
[/THINK]
[2026-06-11T03:31:18.055Z] [THINK]
-package ROS2 project, not a widely-distributed library

The P
[/THINK]
[2026-06-11T03:31:18.475Z] [THINK]
impl idiom adds complexity (two sets of forwarding methods, heap allocation, pointer
