So the `sleep(4)` is right
[/THINK]
[2026-06-11T05:43:24.288Z] [THINK]
 after the takeoff call (line 1004-1021) and before the main control loop (line 1025).

The purpose
[/THINK]
[2026-06-11T05:43:24.695Z] [THINK]
 is clear: wait for the drone to actually take off and reach the target
[/THINK]
[2026-06-11T05:43:25.116Z] [THINK]
 altitude before entering the main control loop. Takeoff is a command
[/THINK]
[2026-06-11T05:43:25.534Z] [THINK]
 that takes time - you send the command, it says
[/THINK]
[2026-06-11T05:43:25.937Z] [THINK]
 "success" (meaning the command was ACCEPTED), but the drone still needs several
[/THINK]
[2026-06-11T05:43:26.344Z] [THINK]
 seconds to actually spin up motors and climb to the target altitude.

Without this sleep, the main
[/THINK]
[2026-06-11T05:43:26.759Z] [THINK]
 control loop would immediately start trying to control position/velocity while the drone is still on
[/THINK]
[2026-06-11T05:43:27.172Z] [THINK]
 the ground.

Is it necessary? Well, it's a crude but effective way to wait
[/THINK]
[2026-06-11T05:43:27.617Z] [THINK]
 for takeoff. A better approach would be to poll the drone's altitude until it's
[/THINK]
[2026-06-11T05:43:28.029Z] [THINK]
 above some threshold. But for a simple script, `sleep(4)` works
[/THINK]
[2026-06-11T05:43:28.454Z] [THINK]
. Whether it's "necessary" depends on the drone's behavior - if the control loop might
[/THINK]
[2026-06-11T05:43:28.907Z] [THINK]
 send competing commands during takeoff, then yes, it prevents conflict.

